title: Cross sections of (n,x) reactions on cerium isotopes induced by D-T neutrons

x4freetext: Cross sections of (n,x) reactions on cerium isotopes
induced by D-T neutrons

x4freetext: 300 kV Cockroft-Walton (OKTAVIAN)
Neutrons were produced with a deuteron beam
energy of 265 keV and a beam current of 250 uA. The
stability of the neutron flux was monitored by using
a scintillator detector. The absolute value of
neutron flux was determined by neutron activation
analysis. The intensity of the neutron source was
estimated to be about 1.5E11 neutron/sec by the
monitor reaction 27Al(n,a)24Na. The neutron energy
was calibrated by the cross section ratio of
90Zr(n,2n)89Zr to 93Nb(n,2n)92mNb reactions.
A low background, high efficiency HPGe
detector with a relative efficiency of about 68% and
an energy resolution of 1.7 keV (FWHM) at 1.33 MeV.
The efficiency of the detector was pre-calibrated
using various standard gamma sources, which are 60Co,
Samples (CeO2 powder of 99.99% pure, natural isotopic
composition) were pressed into circular lamina with a
diameter of about 14 mm and a thickness of about 1
mm. Each of the sample was covered by a polyethylene
bag and then sandwiched between two monitor Al
(99.99% pure, 50 um thick) foils and standard Nb and
Zr (99.99% pure, 0.5 mm thick) foil.
The samples were placed at 45 deg and 85 deg
angles relative to the deuterium beam direction and
centered about the T-Ti target at a distance of 35 mm,
were irradiated for about 8 h. The length of cooling
and measuring time mainly depends on the half life of
the isotope to be measured. After the irradiation and
cooling, the gamma-activities of 135Ce, 137Ce, 139Ce,
141Ce, 140La, 142La, 137mBa, 139Ba and 143Ce were
measured. Four characteristic gamma peaks were marked
for 135Ce and 140La products, and one characteristic
gamma peak was marked for 137mCe, 139Ce, 141Ce, 142La,
137mBa, 139Ba and 143Ce products, respectively.
Qiang Wang (2021-3-3):
The values were obtained by fitting and interpolating
the data of ENDF/B-VII.1
The activity correction factor given by F = fc*fg*fs.
fc, fg, and fs are the correction factors for the
coincidence summing effect factor of cascade
gamma-rays, the geometry correction factor, and the
gamma-ray self-absorption correction factor of the
sample at a given gamma-energy.
